                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">On the Lying Prophets.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Therefore thus says the Lord God; because</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">you have spoken vanity, and seen lies,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">therefore, behold, I am against you, says</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">the Lord God, and my hand shall be upon</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">the prophets that see vanity, and that</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">divine lies; they shall not be in the</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">assembly of my people, neither shall</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">they be written in the writing of the</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">house of <placeName>Israel</placeName>, neither
                                        shall they</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">enter into the land of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName>, and</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Joy shall know that I am thy Lord</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">God.    Ezekiel XIII. 889.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Various are the ways practiced by seducers<lb/> of
                                        all times, and chiefly by such who proposed<lb/> themselves
                                        to seduce the people of God; the most<lb/> dangerous,
                                        however, were such as begun with their<lb/> preaching, of a
                                        pretended improving of hearts and<lb/> reason of mankind;
                                        disguising as much as possible,<lb/> their irreligious
                                        conduct, and the real feelings<lb/> of their depraved
                                        heart.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I. O. begun <sic>likwise</sic> with his sermon on
                                        the<lb/> mount, saying: Thank not that I am come to
                                        destroy<lb/> the</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>the laws or the prophets. I am not come to destroy<lb/> but to
                                                  <sic>fulfil</sic>; for verily, I say unto you,
                                        till heaven<lb/> and earth past one jot or one little shall
                                        in no wise<lb/> past from the law till all be fulfilled.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">He and her disciples ended with the abolition<lb/>
                                        of nearly all, the precepts taught by
                                                  <persName>Moses</persName> and<lb/> the
                                        prophets.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">However, our readers could be induced to
                                        believe,<lb/> that for <hi rend="underline">a member of the
                                                  Jewish religious society</hi><lb/> it might be <hi
                                                  rend="underline">his mission to strive
                                                  earnestly</hi><lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">to render his religion that of the
                                                  world</hi>; not<lb/> at all, God has given 613
                                        commandments only<lb/> to the Israelites, for other nations
                                        Seven<lb/> commandments; and from there was already<lb/>
                                        revealed six to <persName>Adam</persName> and after that
                                        time<lb/> re<add>?</add> to <persName>Noah</persName> with
                                        the addition of <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add><add>?</add> Talmud
                                        Sanhevrin<add>?</add><lb/> folio 56. and Tad <add>?</add>
                                                  Hilchat<add>?</add> Melachim.</p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>And if we observe attentively the course of events we<lb/> see a
                                                  <sic>graduel</sic> progress in the amelioration of
                                        the religious<lb/> state of the Christians and
                                                  <sic>principaly</sic> under<add>?</add> the<lb/>
                                        Protestant sects who by the reading of our holy songs,<lb/>
                                        here learn to revere the God of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName> as the Lord<lb/> of
                                        all mankind; undoubtful we may apply on<lb/> thousands of
                                        them the sentence of the Talmud<lb/> (<add>Hebrew</add>)
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">You see by this that the observation of the
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> is sufficient for other nations<lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> And if God has chosen us as the
                                                  <sic>ofspring</sic> of his<lb/> beloved servants
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> to be a priestly<lb/> kingdom
                                        and a holy people, it is by no means our sake<lb/> to strive
                                        to render our religion that of the word; in the<lb/>
                                        contrary, we begin always with making official<lb/>ties when
                                        somebody of other nations would present him<lb/>self to
                                        accept our precepts and laws (Tez Talmad Taba<lb/>moth folio 47.)<lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>.</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p><add>Hebrew</add><lb/> and ibidem <add>Hebrew</add></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">If any body would in the contrary ascertain that
                                        it<lb/> might be our duty to make prosylites, he would show
                                        never<lb/> to have understood <add>Hebrew</add> or that he
                                        is<lb/> a deceiver and willing to seduce us; and every
                                        Israelite of<lb/> sound religious principles will agree that
                                        in con<lb/>cordance of the cited places the intention of the
                                        Talmud<lb/> (Perachim folio 80) <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add></p>
                              <p>is only that by the exile<add>?</add> of our nation the
                                        gentiles<lb/> being somewhat acquainted with our
                                        scriptures<lb/> will find back in them this a long time ago
                                        for<lb/> their lost covenant that God with
                                                  <persName>Noah</persName> and his Gene<lb/>rations
                                        and that by the word <add>Hebrew</add> here must<lb/> be
                                        understood <add>Hebrew</add></p>
                              <p>And if there be some other hidden meaning in it: <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add> surely it will never<lb/> be like the
                                        absurd idea of false prophets of our times,<lb/> that we
                                        should reform our system in order to make <hi
                                                  rend="underline">by it</hi> the<lb/> unity of God
                                        the basis of the faith of mankind.</p>
                              <p><add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>!</p>
                              <pb n="5"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="6"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="7"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>Mon Feb 19, 1854</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>N.Y.</placeName>
                                        <date>Rosh Hodesh Adar (March)</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><date>1854</date>.</p>
                              <p>Honored Sir:</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">This is followed by several lines which I<lb/>
                                        desire to see included in the “Occident.” That is,<lb/>
                                        provided you consider them worthwhile for the<lb/> public. I
                                        am convinced of my weakness in<lb/> the English language
                                        inasmuch as I am<lb/> in this land only a few months. I have
                                        no<lb/> doubt that you will have to make some<lb/> changes
                                        in this and I shall be delighted<lb/> to have you do it if
                                        necessary.</p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">And now, dear Sir, act according to your<lb/>
                                        wisdom for I rejoice over your words greatly<lb/> and am
                                        convinced that your recompense<lb/> is very great. It is a
                                        righteous war<lb/> that you are conducting, and God
                                        will<lb/> strengthen and hearten and bless you<lb/> and make
                                        for you a name among the<lb/> great men of the earth. And
                                        when you<lb/> come to your eternal reward, you<lb/> will
                                        know that you have sown<lb/> righteousness and it has borne
                                        fruit</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Your faithful servant</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <persName role="author">Isaac Selig Papfer</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="8"/>
                              <p>(The enclosed Sermon speaks for itself. It is<lb/> directed against
                                        the “misleading arguments”<lb/> of the reformers. The Hebrew
                                        quotations need<lb/> not be translated for any
                                        particular<lb/> reason. The last page, in Hebrew, adds<lb/>
                                        nothing to what the English says, and<lb/> may have been
                                        written in that language<lb/> because the preacher was
                                        better able to<lb/> express himself in this way).</p>
